<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!DOCTYPE plist PUBLIC "-//Apple//DTD PLIST 1.0//EN" "http://www.apple.com/DTDs/PropertyList-1.0.dtd">
<plist version="1.0">
<dict>
    <!--
        Tauri reads this file at bundle time and merges its keys into the
        generated Info.plist (per `bundle.macOS.infoPlist` in tauri.conf.json
        — and the Tauri 2 bundler also auto-discovers an Info.plist sitting
        next to tauri.conf.json). Keep this file minimal: usage strings for
        the OS-level TCC permission prompts only.

        Without these strings, prod-signed builds crash the moment cpal
        opens an input stream (NSMicrophoneUsageDescription) or enigo
        types into the focused app (NSAccessibilityUsageDescription).
        Input Monitoring is granted via TCC at runtime — no plist key
        needed, but the user still has to flip the toggle in System
        Settings → Privacy & Security → Input Monitoring for rdev's
        global keyboard hook to fire when boothrflow isn't focused.
    -->
    <key>NSMicrophoneUsageDescription</key>
    <string>boothrflow needs microphone access to capture your voice for dictation. Audio is transcribed locally and never sent to a server unless you explicitly configure a cloud LLM.</string>

    <key>NSAccessibilityUsageDescription</key>
    <string>boothrflow uses Accessibility to paste your transcribed text into the focused application after you release the dictation hotkey.</string>

    <key>NSAppleEventsUsageDescription</key>
    <string>boothrflow uses AppleEvents to detect the focused application so cleanup can match its tone (e.g., formal in Mail, casual in Slack).</string>
</dict>
</plist>
